## OpenTelemetry (OTLP HTTP) setup

The notifier speaks the OTLP-HTTP JSON protocol against your OpenTelemetry collector's `/v1/logs` endpoint. Any OTEL-compatible backend (Grafana Cloud, Datadog, Honeycomb, New Relic, Splunk Observability, self-hosted collectors) works.

### Salesforce setup

- **Webhook mode**: paste the full OTLP-HTTP logs endpoint URL into `Webhook URL` (e.g. `https://otlp-gateway.example.com/v1/logs`). The notifier does NOT append `/v1/logs` in this mode - include it in the URL.
- **Named Credential mode**: create a Named Credential with the base URL of your collector. The notifier appends `/v1/logs` automatically. Most managed collectors (Grafana Cloud, Datadog) authenticate via an Authorization header - configure that on the Named Credential's External Credential.

### Recipient config JSON

Customize headers and OTEL resource attributes per recipient:

```json
{
  "headers": {
    "X-Scope-OrgID": "your-tenant-id"
  },
  "resourceAttributes": {
    "service.name": "salesforce-nebula-logger",
    "deployment.environment": "prod"
  }
}
```

- `headers` (optional): additional HTTP headers to send with each request. Common use cases are tenant identifiers (Grafana `X-Scope-OrgID`), auth (Datadog `DD-API-KEY`), or observability-tool routing hints.
- `resourceAttributes` (optional): map of OTEL resource attribute name to value. These land on every log record sent to your collector and get indexed as top-level attributes in your observability tool. Prefer OTEL semantic conventions (`service.name`, `service.version`, `deployment.environment`, `host.name`).
